04_spring_di.description:
Spring prefers constructor injection because dependencies become explicit and the object can be fully initialized at creation.

```java
@Service
class OrderService {
    OrderService(PaymentClient client) { ... }
}
```

05_bean_lifecycle.description:
A Spring bean is an object created and managed by the container rather than by arbitrary `new` calls throughout the codebase.

```java
@Component
class Clock { }
```

Container ownership is what makes injection possible.

07_jpa_entity.description:
A JPA entity represents row identity over time. Its lifecycle matters, not only its field values.

```java
@Entity
class Member { @Id Long id; }
```

09_transaction_boundary.description:
A transaction should wrap a unit of work that must succeed or fail together.

```java
@Transactional
public void transfer(...)
```

10_repository_queries.description:
A repository hides data access details behind a domain-oriented interface.

```java
interface UserRepository {
    User findById(Long id);
}
```

This gives services a cleaner contract than embedding SQL everywhere.

18_component_scan.description:
Spring can discover `@Service` or `@Repository` classes automatically.

```java
@Service
class UserService {}
```

The container registers the component and wires it into the object graph.

20_proxy_self_invocation.description:
Features such as `@Transactional` are often applied through proxies.

```java
service.outer();
this.inner();
```

A plain self-call can bypass proxy interception.
